{
    "measure": "Valid - Neutral",
    "task": "Spatial (Posner) Cueing task",
    "constructs": [
        "Attention",
        "Response Selection"
    ],
    "comments": "The Valid - Neutral measure in the Spatial Cueing task primarily taps into attentional processes, specifically the benefit of orienting attention to the correct location. It also involves response selection as participants must respond to the target. The difference between valid and neutral trials reflects the facilitation effect of spatial attention, where valid cues lead to faster responses compared to neutral cues. This measure captures the ability to use spatial information to guide attention and prepare for a response."
}

{
    "measure": "Valid - Neutral",
    "task": "Spatial (Posner) Cueing task",
    "constructs": [
        "Attention",
        "Goal Selection",
        "Response Selection"
    ],
    "comments": "The Valid - Neutral measure in the Spatial Cueing task primarily assesses attentional benefits of valid cues. This measure reflects the advantage in processing speed or accuracy when attention is correctly directed to the target location. It involves attention allocation, goal-directed selection of the cued location, and facilitated response selection due to enhanced processing at the attended location. The difference between valid and neutral trials isolates the benefit of spatial attention, making it a sensitive measure of attentional orienting and its impact on information processing."
}

{
    "measure": "Valid - Neutral",
    "task": "Spatial (Posner) Cueing task",
    "constructs": [
        "Attention",
        "Goal Selection"
    ],
    "comments": "The 'Valid - Neutral' measure in the Spatial Cueing task primarily assesses attentional orienting and the benefit of valid spatial cues. It reflects the efficiency of attentional allocation to a cued location (valid trials) compared to a baseline condition without spatial information (neutral trials). This measure taps into both 'Attention' as it involves the direction and maintenance of attentional focus, and 'Goal Selection' as participants use the cue information to prepare for the upcoming target location. The difference between valid and neutral trials represents the facilitation effect of spatial cueing on attentional deployment and subsequent processing."
}

{
    "measure": "Valid - Neutral",
    "task": "Spatial (Posner) Cueing task",
    "constructs": [
        "Attention",
        "Goal Selection",
        "Response Selection"
    ],
    "comments": "The 'Valid - Neutral' measure in the Spatial Cueing task primarily assesses the benefit of attentional orienting. It reflects the ability to use spatial cues to allocate attention to a specific location, which improves processing speed and accuracy. This measure involves attention (orienting and engaging), goal selection (using the cue to prepare for the target), and response selection (preparing to respond to the target at the cued location). The difference between valid and neutral trials highlights the advantage of having a specific attentional focus versus a distributed attention state."
}

